Effective field theory for resonant wino dark matter

Evan Johnson johnson.6036@osu.edu â€ƒâ€ƒ Hong Zhang zhang.5676@osu.edu â€ƒâ€ƒ Eric Braaten braaten.1@osu.edu Department of Physics, The Ohio State University, Columbus, OHÂ 43210, USA
Abstract

Enhancements in WIMP annihilation rates have been identified with a nonperturbative â€œSommerfeld enhancementâ€ arising from the exchange of light mediators. At certain critical values of the WIMP mass, the enhancement is increased dramatically due to a zero-energy resonance at the WIMP-pair threshold. For masses near these critical values, WIMP scattering processes are accurately described by an effective field theory where WIMPs have nonperturbative zero-range contact interactions. The effective field theory is controlled by a renormalization-group fixed point at which the WIMPs are degenerate in mass and their scattering length is infinite. If the WIMPs can exchange massless mediators, the resulting long-range interaction must also be treated nonperturbatively. We develop an effective field theory for Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(2)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ2SU(2)-triplet dark matter, which have short-range weak and long-range electromagnetic interactions. We refer to these dark matter particles as winos. The long-range Coulomb interaction between charged winos is resummed to all orders. The parameters of the effective field theory can be determined by matching wino-wino scattering amplitudes calculated by solving the SchrÃ¶dinger equation with a potential describing exchange of electroweak gauge bosons. With Coulomb resummation, the effective field theory at leading order gives a good description of the low-energy two-body observables for winos.

I Introduction

Weakly interacting massive particles (WIMPs) are one of the best motivated candidates for a dark matter particle. Stable particles with weak interactions with masses roughly at the electroweak scale are naturally produced in the early universe and freeze out with a relic abundance comparable to the observed mass density of dark matter Kolb:1990vq ; Steigman:2012nb . If the WIMP mass Mğ‘€M is in the TeV range, the self-interactions of nonrelativistic WIMPs are complicated by a nonperturbative effect pointed out by Hisano et al. Hisano:2002fk . Exchanges of gauge bosons must be summed to all orders in the gauge coupling constant and can provide a nonperturbative â€œSommerfeld enhancementâ€ to low-energy scattering and annihilation cross sections.

For certain critical values of the WIMP mass Mğ‘€M, the enhancement is increased dramatically due to a zero-energy resonance at the WIMP-pair threshold. When the resonance is in the S-wave channel, the enhancement in WIMP cross sections occurs over a broader range of Mğ‘€M than in higher partial waves. A feature unique to the S-wave channel is the dynamical generation of a length scale, the scattering length ağ‘a, which can be orders of magnitude larger than the range of the weak interactions.

In a fundamental quantum field theory, WIMPs interact through the exchange of gauge bosons through local interactions. The Sommerfeld enhancement can be calculated by summing up an infinite number of gauge boson exchange diagrams. In the Milky Way, WIMPs have velocities on the order of 10-â€‹3superscript10-310^{\text{-}3} and can be treated nonrelativistically. The exchange of weak gauge bosons becomes nonperturbative for relative momentum below Î±2â€‹Msubscriptğ›¼2ğ‘€\alpha_{2}M. Photon exchange becomes nonperturbative for relative momentum below Î±â€‹Mğ›¼ğ‘€\alpha M. WIMPs with TeV scale masses and relative velocity on the order of 10-â€‹3superscript10-310^{\text{-}3} therefore have nonperturbative electroweak interactions. This challenge is overcome by solving a SchrÃ¶dinger equation in which WIMPs interact via instantaneous interactions at a distance through a potential generated by the exchange of electroweak gauge bosons. The Sommerfeld enhancement is determined numerically by solving the SchrÃ¶dinger equation with this potential. We refer to this framework as nonrelativistic effective field theory (NREFT) and use it as a microscopic description of the WIMP interactions.

Near the critical values of the WIMP mass, the calculation of scattering observables is further facilitated by employing an effective field theory in which WIMPs interact nonperturbativly through contact interactions and charged WIMPs can exchange photons. We refer to this theory as zero-range effective field theory (ZREFT). In Ref.Â Braaten:2017gpq , we developed the ZREFT for WIMPs that consist of the neutral dark-matter particle w0superscriptğ‘¤0w^{0} and charged WIMPs w+superscriptğ‘¤w^{+} and wâˆ’superscriptğ‘¤w^{-} with a slightly larger mass. We refer to these WIMPs as winos, because the fundamental theory describing them could be the minimal supersymmetric standard model (MSSM) in a region of parameter space where the neutral wino is the lightest supersymmetric particle.

In Ref.Â Braaten:2017gpq , the ZREFT for winos is developed for winos with short-range weak interactions only. It is shown to be a systematically improvable effective field theory by calculating wino-wino scattering observables to NLO in the ZREFT power counting. We build on the results in Ref.Â Braaten:2017gpq by including the effects of Coulomb resummation in the interactions between charged winos and show that the theory gives good agreement even at leading order, where there is a single free parameter. This paper serves to summarize the main results of Ref.Â Braaten:2017kci , presented here without derivation. In Ref.Â BJZ-Annihilation , we complete the effective field theory by including the effects of wino-pair annihilation into electroweak gauge bosons.

This paper is organized as follows. In Sec.Â II, we present the fundamental relativistic quantum field theory describing winos and their electroweak interactions. In Sec.Â III, we describe the nonrelativistic treatment of wino scattering processes by solving a SchrÃ¶dinger equation. In Sec.Â IV, we introduce the zero-range model that describes winos with nonperturbative local interactions, and carry out the Coulomb resummation. In Sec.Â V, we define the zero-range effective field theory by identifying the appropriate renormalization group fixed point and a power counting for perturbations around that fixed point. In Sec.Â VI, we compare results calculated numerically by solving the SchrÃ¶digner equation with results calculated analytically in ZREFT at leading order. We conclude in Sec.Â VII.

II Fundamental theory

We assume the dark-matter particle is the neutral member of an Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(2)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ2SU(2) triplet of Majorana fermions with zero hypercharge. The Lorentz-invariant quantum field theory that provides a fundamental description of these fermions could simply be an extension of the Standard Model with this additional Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(2)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ2SU(2) multiplet and with a symmetry that forbids the decay of the fermion into Standard Model particles. The fundamental theory could also be the Minimal Supersymmetric Standard Model (MSSM) in a region of parameter space where the lightest supersymmetric particle is a wino-like neutralino. In either case, we refer to the particles in the Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(2)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ2SU(2) multiplet as winos. We denote the neutral wino by w0superscriptğ‘¤0w^{0} and the charged winos by w+superscriptğ‘¤w^{+} and wâˆ’superscriptğ‘¤w^{-}. For the neutral wino to be a stable dark matter candidate, the masses of the neutral and charged winos must be split by a small amount Î´ğ›¿\delta. In the MSSM, the mass splitting arises from radiative corrections and has a value Î´=170ğ›¿170\delta=170Â MeV.

The winos can be represented by a triplet of Majorana spinor fields. We will take the neutral wino mass Mğ‘€M to be an adustable parameter, and we keep the wino mass splitting fixed at Î´=170ğ›¿170\delta=170Â MeV. The most important interactions of the winos are those with the electroweak gauge bosons: the photon, the WÂ±superscriptğ‘Šplus-or-minusW^{\pm}, and the Z0superscriptğ‘0Z^{0}. The relevant Standard Model parameters are the mass mW=80.4subscriptğ‘šğ‘Š80.4m_{W}=80.4Â GeV of the WÂ±superscriptğ‘Šplus-or-minusW^{\pm}, the mass mZ=91.2subscriptğ‘šğ‘91.2m_{Z}=91.2Â GeV of the Z0superscriptğ‘0Z^{0}, the Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(2)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ2SU(2) coupling constant Î±2=1/29.5subscriptğ›¼2129.5\alpha_{2}=1/29.5, the electromagnetic coupling constant Î±=1/137.04ğ›¼1137.04\alpha=1/137.04, and the weak mixing angle, which is given by sin2â¡Î¸W=0.231superscript2subscriptğœƒğ‘Š0.231\sin^{2}\theta_{W}=0.231.

IV Zero-Range Model with Coulomb Resummation

The important momentum scales for wino interactions discussed thus far are momentum scales associated with weak exchange: Î±2â€‹Msubscriptğ›¼2ğ‘€\alpha_{2}M, photon exchange: Î±â€‹Mğ›¼ğ‘€\alpha M, and transitions between channels: Î”=2â€‹Mâ€‹Î´Î”2ğ‘€ğ›¿\Delta=\sqrt{2M\delta}. V ZREFT with Coulomb resummation

The zero-range model with transition amplitudes given by the matrix in Eq.Â (17) has two coupled scattering channels with different energy thresholds. An effective field theory can be defined most rigorously by identifying a renormalization-group fixed point. Systematically improving accuracy is then ensured by adding to the Lagrangian operators with increasingly higher scaling dimensions.

More convienently, the matrix ğœ¸ğœ¸\bm{\gamma} in Eq.Â (25) can be expressed as a power series in p2superscriptğ‘2p^{2} with coefficients that define scattering parameters. Systematic improvement can be achieved if we can identify a power counting that determines the improvement in the accuracy of a model that can be obtained by including each of the parameters. To define the power counting, we introduce the generic momentum scale Qğ‘„Q described by the effective theory. We take the energy Eğ¸E and the mass splitting Î´ğ›¿\delta to be of order Q2/Msuperscriptğ‘„2ğ‘€Q^{2}/M. We also introduce a momentum scale Î›Î›\Lambda that can be regarded as the ultraviolet cutoff of the effective field theory. The physical interpretation of Î›Î›\Lambda is the smallest momentum scale beyond the domain of applicability of the effective field theory. In the case of winos, Î›Î›\Lambda is the inverse range mWsubscriptğ‘šğ‘Šm_{W} of the weak interactions. The power-counting scheme identifies how each parameter scales as a power of Qğ‘„Q and Î›Î›\Lambda. The transition amplitudes ğ’œiâ€‹jâ€‹(E)subscriptğ’œğ‘–ğ‘—ğ¸\mathcal{A}_{ij}(E) can be expanded in powers of Q/Î›ğ‘„Î›Q/\Lambda. The systematically improving accuracy of the effective field theory is ensured by including parameters whose leading contributions to ğ’œiâ€‹jâ€‹(E)subscriptğ’œğ‘–ğ‘—ğ¸\mathcal{A}_{ij}(E) scale with increasingly higher powers of Q/Î›ğ‘„Î›Q/\Lambda.

V.1 Renormalization-group fixed points

Lensky and Birse have carried out a careful renormalization-group (RG) analysis of the two-particle sector for the field theory with two coupled scattering channels with zero-range interactions Lensky:2011he . Three distinct RG fixed points were identified corresponding to zero, one, or two resonances at the scattering threshold. For wino scattering, the appropriate fixed point has a single resonance, and we refer to it as the single-channel-unitarity fixed point. At this fixed point, the two scattering channels have the same threshold (Î´=0ğ›¿0\delta=0), and are mixed by an angle Ï•italic-Ï•\phi. There is nontrivial scattering in a single channel that is a linear combination of the neutral channel w0â€‹w0superscriptğ‘¤0superscriptğ‘¤0w^{0}w^{0} and the charged channel w+â€‹wâˆ’superscriptğ‘¤superscriptğ‘¤w^{+}w^{-} with mixing angle Ï•italic-Ï•\phi. In that channel, the cross section saturates the S-wave unitarity bound. There is no scattering in the orthogonal channel. The single-channel-unitarity fixed point is the most natural one for describing a system with a single fine tuning, such as the tuning of the wino mass Mğ‘€M to a unitarity value where there is an S-wave resonance at the threshold.

Unitarity constrains the coefficients of the expansions in powers of p2superscriptğ‘2p^{2} and Î”2superscriptÎ”2\Delta^{2} to be real. At the fixed point, there is a single relevant operator with scaling dimension âˆ’11-1. It corresponds to the parameter c00(u)subscriptsuperscriptğ‘ğ‘¢00c^{(u)}_{00} in the coefficient of ğ“Ÿuâ€‹(Ï•)subscriptğ“Ÿğ‘¢italic-Ï•\bm{\mathcal{P}}_{u}(\phi) in Eq.Â (V.2). All the other operators are irrelevant operators with scaling dimensions 1 or higher. The corresponding parameters can be treated perturbatively. The sums in Eq.Â (V.2) can be truncated to include only terms with scaling dimensions below some maximum. This truncation defines a field theory with a finite number of parameters. By increasing the maximum scaling dimension, we obtain a systematically improvable sequence of field theories. They define an effective field theory that we refer to as zero-range effective field theory (ZREFT).

In this section we determine the accuracy of ZREFT at leading order by comparing quantities determined numerically by solving the SchrÃ¶dinger equation using NREFT and calculated analytically using expressions in Sec.Â V.

The result for the leading order S-wave T-matrix in ZREFT is obtained by evaluating Eq.Â (40) at the center-of-mass energy Eğ¸E. Wino-wino cross sections are calculated in NREFT from Eqs.Â (5) and in ZREFT from Eqs.Â (41). The mixing angle is determined by matching the effective range using the result in Eq.Â (47). The mixing angle is shown as a function of the wino mass in the left panel of Fig.Â 7.

The neutral-wino shape parameter s0subscriptğ‘ 0s_{0} is shown as a function of the wino mass Mğ‘€M in the right panel of Fig.Â 7. It is determined in NREFT by solving the SchrÃ¶dinger equation and calculating the effective range expansion in Eq.Â (8). In ZREFT at leading order, it is found using the expression in Eq.Â (46b) along with the value of the mixing angle. If the matching is carried out as a function of the wino mass, the prediction agrees very well with the NREFT value, as is shown by the solid curve. The cross sections have the most dramatic energy dependence at a unitarity mass, where Ïƒ0â†’0subscriptğœâ†’00\sigma_{0\to 0} saturates the unitarity bound in Eq.Â (7a) in the low energy limit. The cross sections are calculated in NREFT using Eqs.Â (5). The neutral wino S-wave elastic cross section is shown as a function of the center-of-mass energy Eğ¸E in Fig.Â 8.

The leading order ZREFT prediction reproduces all of the important features of the NREFT result, including the resonances just below the charged-wino-pair threshold at E=2â€‹Î´ğ¸2ğ›¿E=2\delta.

The charged wino S-wave elastic cross section Ïƒ1â†’1subscriptğœâ†’11\sigma_{1\to 1} also displays oscillations in the center-of-mass energy Eğ¸E. These are not resonances since they do not saturate the unitarity bound. These oscillations are present in the S-wave cross section. Contributions from other partial waves interfere, and the total cross section has a smooth dependence on the energy.

To examine the resonances in the neutral channel and oscillations in the charged channel, in Fig.Â 9, we divide the elastic cross sections by the respective unitarity bounds in Eq.Â (7). The neutral-wino S-wave elastic cross section in ZREFT displays zeros at the energies Ensubscriptğ¸ğ‘›E_{n} in Eq.Â (21). In NREFT, the locations of the resonances and zeros are slightly increased. The ZREFT prediction is still an excellent approximation to the cross section. The charged-wino S-wave elastic cross section does not have resonances or zeros, but has rapid oscillations that increase in frequency as the energy approaches the threshold. The leading order ZREFT prediction displays the same oscillations, with an amplitude smaller by about 40%.

VII Conclusions

The Standard Model does not contain a particle that can compose the dark matter. Models of dark matter are thus models of physics beyond the Standard Model. One of the most natural ways to extend the Standard Model to include possible dark matter particles is to introduce new multiplets of the Standard Model gauge groups along with some symmetry that forbids their decay into Standard Model particles. One possibility is to introduce an Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(2)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ2SU(2) triplet with zero hypercharge so that one component is electrically neutral and can play the role of dark matter. Such an extension is already included in models of supersymmetry where the new Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(2)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ2SU(2) triplet is the wino. One way around these difficulties is by employing the framework of nonrelativistic effective field theory (NREFT) in which winos interact through a weak-interaction potential and in which charged winos also interact by exchanging photons. One of the primary motivations for the development of ZREFT for winos was the â€œSommerfeld enhancementâ€ of the annihilation of a pair of neutral winos into electroweak gauge bosons. Wino-pair annihilation not only provides additional wino-wino scattering channels, but also affects other aspects of the few-body physics for low-energy winos. The effects of wino-pair annihilation are usually suppressed by Î±22â€‹mW2/M2superscriptsubscriptğ›¼22superscriptsubscriptğ‘šğ‘Š2superscriptğ‘€2\alpha_{2}^{2}m_{W}^{2}/M^{2}, which is roughly 10âˆ’6superscript10610^{-6} for Mğ‘€M in the TeV region, but they can be dramatic near a unitarity mass. For example, the neutral-wino elastic cross section does not actually diverge at a unitarity mass, but instead has a very narrow peak as a function of Mğ‘€M Blum:2016nrz . The finite maximum cross section comes from unitarization of the wino-pair annihilation, which has not been taken into account in most previous calculations of the Sommerfeld enhancement factor. A naive estimate of the maximum cross section is 6 orders of magnitude higher than the cross section above the charged-wino pair threshold. The effects of wino-pair annihilation on low-energy winos can be taken into account in ZREFT by analytically continuing real interaction parameters to complex values. ZREFT can be used to provide analytic results for low-energy wino-wino cross sections and for inclusive wino-pair annihilation rates, including the effects of the unitarization of wino-pair annihilation.
